GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 1127
Short Title: Affordable Maternal Access & Cancer Care Act. (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives Belk, Clark, G. Brown, and Prather (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Appropriations, if favorable, Rules, Calendar, and Operations of the House
April 30, 2026
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT ENACTING THE AFFORDABLE MATERNAL ACCESS AND CANCER CARE
3 ACT TO ESTABLISH AND FUND A MATERNAL CARE ACCESS GRANT PROGRAM
4 AND A PROSTATE CANCER CONTROL PROGRAM; AND TO PROVIDE HEALTH
5 COVERAGE PARITY FOR SUPPLEMENTAL AND DIAGNOSTIC BREAST IMAGING.
6 Whereas, North Carolina continues to face preventable disparities in maternal health
7 outcomes, including higher rates of maternal mortality and severe maternal morbidity among
8 marginalized and underserved populations; and
9 Whereas, community-based, culturally respectful, evidence-based supports can
10 improve maternal health outcomes by addressing both clinical needs and social determinants of
11 health before, during, and after pregnancy; and
12 Whereas, uninsured and underinsured men with elevated prostate cancer risk often
13 face delayed screening and follow-up, resulting in later detection and worse outcomes; and
14 Whereas, patients should not face greater financial barriers to medically necessary
15 diagnostic or supplemental breast imaging than they face for screening mammography; and
16 Whereas, improving early detection, access to care, and continuity of care promotes
17 better health outcomes and advances the public interest in a healthier North Carolina; Now,
18 therefore,
19 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
20
21 PART I. MATERNAL CARE ACCESS GRANT PROGRAM
22 SECTION 1.1.(a) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this section:
23 (1) Culturally respectful congruent. – Sensitive to and respectful of the preferred
24 cultural values, beliefs, world view, and practices of the patient, and aware
25 that cultural differences between patients and health care providers or other
26 service providers must be proactively addressed to ensure that patients receive
27 equitable, high-quality services that meet their needs.
28 (2) Department. – The North Carolina Department of Health and Human
29 Services.
30 (3) Postpartum. – The one-year period beginning on the last day of a woman's
31 pregnancy.
32 SECTION 1.1.(b) Establishment of Grant Program. – The Department shall
33 establish and administer a Maternal Care Access Grant Program to award competitive grants to
34 eligible entities to establish or expand programs for the prevention of maternal mortality and
35 severe maternal morbidity among marginalized and underserved populations. The Department
*H1127-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 shall establish eligibility requirements for program participation which shall, at a minimum,
2 require that applicants be organizations led by individuals from communities that have
3 historically experienced disparities in accessing health and human services.
4 SECTION 1.1.(c) Outreach and Application Assistance. – Beginning July 1, 2026,
5 the Department shall (i) conduct outreach to encourage eligible applicants to apply for grants
6 under this program and (ii) provide application assistance to eligible applicants on best practices
7 for applying for grants under this program. In conducting the outreach required by this section,
8 the Department shall give special consideration to eligible applicants that meet the following
9 criteria:
10 (1) Are based in, and provide support for, communities with high rates of adverse
11 maternal health outcomes and significant racial and ethnic disparities in
12 maternal health outcomes.
13 (2) Are led by women from marginalized and underserved populations.
14 (3) Offer programs and resources that are aligned with evidence-based practices
15 for improving maternal health outcomes for marginalized and underserved
16 populations.
17 SECTION 1.1.(d) Grant Awards. – In awarding grants under this section, the
18 Department shall, to the extent possible, award grants to recipients to reflect different areas of
19 the State. The Department shall not award a single grant for less than ten thousand dollars
20 ($10,000) or more than fifty thousand dollars ($50,000) per grant recipient. In selecting grant
21 recipients, the Department shall give special consideration to eligible applicants that meet all of
22 the following criteria:
23 (1) Meet all of the criteria specified in subdivisions (1) through (3) of subsection
24 (c) of this section.
25 (2) Offer programs and resources designed in consultation with and intended for
26 marginalized and underserved populations.
27 (3) Offer programs and resources in the communities in which they are located
28 that include any of the following activities:
29 a. Promoting maternal mental health and maternal substance use disorder
30 treatments that are aligned with evidence-based practices for
31 improving maternal mental health outcomes for marginalized and
32 underserved populations.
33 b. Addressing social determinants of health for women in the prenatal
34 and postpartum periods, including, but not limited to, any of the
35 following:
36 1. Inadequate housing.
37 2. Transportation barriers.
38 3. Poor nutrition and a lack of access to healthy foods.
39 4. Need for lactation support.
40 5. Need for lead abatement and other efforts to improve air and
41 water quality.
42 6. Lack of access to child care.
43 7. Need for baby supplies such as diapers, formula, clothing, baby
44 and child equipment, and safe car seat installation.
45 8. Need for wellness and stress management programs.
46 9. Education about maternal health and well-being.
47 10. Need for coordination across safety net and social support
48 services and programs.
49 11. Barriers to employment.
Page 2 House Bill 1127-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 c. Promoting evidence-based health literacy and pregnancy, childbirth,
2 and parenting education for women in the prenatal and postpartum
3 periods, including group-based programs and peer support groups.
4 d. Providing individually tailored support from doulas and other perinatal
5 health workers to women from pregnancy through the postpartum
6 period.
7 e. Providing culturally respectful congruent training to perinatal health
8 workers such as doulas, community health workers, peer supporters,
9 certified lactation consultants, nutritionists and dietitians, social
10 workers, home visitors, and navigators.
11 f. Conducting or supporting research on issues affecting black maternal
12 health.
13 g. Developing other programs and resources that address
14 community-specific needs for women in the prenatal and postpartum
15 periods and are aligned with evidence-based practices for improving
16 maternal health outcomes for marginalized and underserved
17 populations.
18 SECTION 1.1.(e) Technical Assistance to Grant Recipients. – The Department shall
19 provide technical assistance to grant recipients regarding all of the following:
20 (1) Capacity building to establish or expand programs to prevent adverse maternal
21 health outcomes among marginalized and underserved populations.
22 (2) Best practices in data collection, measurement, evaluation, and reporting.
23 (3) Planning centered around sustaining programs implemented with grant funds
24 to prevent maternal mortality and severe maternal morbidity among
25 marginalized and underserved populations when the grant funds have been
26 expended.
27 SECTION 1.1.(f) There is appropriated from the General Fund to the Department of
28 Health and Human Services, Division of Public Health, the sum of five million dollars
29 ($5,000,000) in recurring funds for the 2026-2027 fiscal year to be used and allocated as follows:
30 (1) Ninety-three thousand five hundred thirteen dollars ($93,513) in recurring
31 funds for the 2026-2027 fiscal year to establish a full-time, permanent Public
32 Health Program Coordinator IV position within the Department dedicated to
33 performing the following duties:
34 a. Providing application assistance to Maternal Care Access Grant
35 Program applicants.
36 b. Providing technical assistance to Maternal Care Access Grant Program
37 recipients.
38 c. Preparing the reports due under Section 1.1(h) of this Part.
39 (2) Four million nine hundred six thousand four hundred eighty-seven dollars
40 ($4,906,487) in recurring funds for the 2026-2027 fiscal year to be allocated
41 to the Maternal Care Access Grant Program authorized by this Part. The
42 Department may use up to one percent (1%) of these funds for administrative
43 purposes related to the grant program. The balance of these funds shall be used
44 to operate the grant program.
45 SECTION 1.1.(g) The Department is authorized to hire one full-time, permanent
46 Public Health Program Coordinator IV position to perform the duties described in subdivision
47 (f)(1) of this section.
48 SECTION 1.1.(h) Reports. – The Department shall submit the following reports on
49 the grant program authorized by this section to the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on
50 Health and Human Services and the Fiscal Research Division:
