1 SECTION 3.2. G.S. 58-3-271, as enacted by Section 3.1(a) of this act, reads as
2 rewritten:
3 "§ 58-3-271. Coverage for diagnostic, screening, and supplemental examinations for
4 breast cancer, including mammograms and other imaging, and cervical cancer
5 screening.
6 (a) The following definitions apply in this section:
7 (1) Breast magnetic resonance imaging. – A diagnostic tool that uses a powerful
8 magnetic field, radio waves, and a computer to produce detailed pictures of
9 the structures within the breast.
10 (2) Breast ultrasound. – A noninvasive diagnostic tool that uses high-frequency
11 sound waves to produce detailed images of the breast.
12 (3) Cost-sharing. – A deductible, coinsurance, copayment, and any maximum
13 limitation on the application of a deductible, coinsurance, copayment, or
14 similar out-of-pocket expense.
15 (4) Diagnostic examination for breast cancer. – An examination for breast cancer
16 that is determined by the healthcare provider treating the patient to be
17 medically necessary and appropriate and that may include breast magnetic
18 resonance imaging, breast ultrasound, and diagnostic low-dose
19 mammography to evaluate the abnormality in the breast that meets one of the
20 following criteria:
21 a. Is seen or suspected from a screening examination for breast cancer.
22 b. Is detected by another means of examination.
23 (5) High-deductible health plan. – As defined under the Internal Revenue Code.
24 (6) Low-dose mammography. – A radiologic procedure for the early detection of
25 breast cancer using equipment dedicated specifically for mammography,
26 including a physician's interpretation of the results of the procedure.
27 (7) Screening examination for breast cancer. – Low-dose mammography, or an
28 equivalent procedure, that is used to determine if there is abnormality in the
29 breast.
30 (8) Screening of early detection of cervical cancer. – Examinations and laboratory
31 tests used to detect cervical cancer, including conventional PAP smear
32 screening, liquid-based cytology, and human papilloma virus (HPV) detection
33 methods for women with equivocal findings on cervical cytologic analysis
34 that are subject to the approval of and have been approved by the United States
35 Food and Drug Administration.
36 (9) Section 223. – Section 223 of the Internal Revenue Code or its equivalent.
37 (10) Supplemental examination for breast cancer. – An examination for breast
38 cancer that is determined by the healthcare provider treating the patient to be
39 medically necessary and appropriate and that may include breast magnetic
40 resonance imaging or breast ultrasound to screen for cancer when there is no
41 abnormality seen or suspected if the patient meets either of the following
42 criteria:
43 a. The patient is at increased risk for breast cancer based on the patient's
44 personal medical history or family medical history of breast cancer.
45 b. The patient has a breast cancer risk profile that qualifies the patient
46 based on current recommendations of the United States Preventive
47 Services Task Force, also known as USPSTF.
48 (a)(a1) Every policy or contract of accident or health insurance, and every preferred provider
49 benefit plan under G.S. 58-50-56, that is issued, renewed, or amended on or after January 1, 1992,
50 health benefit plan offered by an insurer in this State shall provide coverage for examinations
51 and laboratory tests for the screening for the early detection of cervical cancer and for low-dose
House Bill 1127-First Edition Page 5

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 screening mammography. The same deductibles, coinsurance, and other limitations as apply to
2 similar services covered under the policy, contract, or plan shall apply to coverage for
3 examinations and laboratory tests for the screening for the early detection of cervical cancer and
4 low-dose screening mammography.
5 (a1) As used in this section, "examinations and laboratory tests for the screening for the
6 early detection of cervical cancer" means conventional PAP smear screening, liquid-based
7 cytology, and human papilloma virus (HPV) detection methods for women with equivocal
8 findings on cervical cytologic analysis that are subject to the approval of and have been approved
9 by the United States Food and Drug Administration.
10 (b) As used in this section, "low-dose screening mammography" means a radiologic
11 procedure for the early detection of breast cancer provided to an asymptomatic woman using
12 equipment dedicated specifically for mammography, including a physician's interpretation of the
13 results of the procedure.
14 (b1) Every health benefit plan offered by an insurer that provides benefits for a diagnostic
15 or supplemental examination for breast cancer shall ensure that the cost-sharing requirements
16 applicable to a diagnostic or supplemental examination for breast cancer are no less favorable
17 than the cost-sharing requirements applicable to low-dose screening mammography for breast
18 cancer.
19 (b2) An insurer shall not be required to reimburse a healthcare provider that is not a
20 contracted provider in the provider network of a health benefit plan offered by the insurer any
21 reimbursement rate more than the rate paid to a provider that has contracted with the insurer to
22 participate in the provider network of the health benefit plan for any of the following services:
23 (1) Diagnostic, screening, or supplemental examination for breast cancer.
24 (2) Low-dose mammography.
25 (3) Breast ultrasound.
26 (4) Breast magnetic resonance imaging.
27 (c) Coverage for low-dose screening mammography shall be provided as follows:
28 (1) One or more mammograms a year, as recommended by a physician, for any
29 woman who is at risk for breast cancer. For purposes of this subdivision, a
30 woman is at risk for breast cancer if any one or more of the following is true:
31 a. The woman has a personal history of breast cancer;cancer.
32 b. The woman has a personal history of biopsy-proven benign breast
33 disease;disease.
34 c. The woman's mother, sister, or daughter has or has had breast cancer;
35 orcancer.
36 d. The woman has not given birth prior to the age of 30;30.
37 (2) One baseline mammogram for any woman 35 through 39 years of age,
38 inclusive;inclusive.
39 (3) A mammogram every other year for any woman 40 through 49 years of age,
40 inclusive, or more frequently upon recommendation of a physician;
41 andphysician.
42 (4) A mammogram every year for any woman 50 years of age or older.
43 (d) Reimbursement for a mammogram authorized under this section shall be made only
44 if the facility in which the mammogram was performed meets mammography accreditation
45 standards established by the North Carolina Medical Care Commission.
46 (e) Coverage for the screening for the early detection of cervical cancer shall be in
47 accordance with the most recently published American Cancer Society American College of
48 Obstetricians and Gynecologists' guidelines or guidelines adopted by the North Carolina
49 Advisory Committee on Cancer Coordination and Control. Coverage shall include the
50 examination, the laboratory fee, and the physician's interpretation of the laboratory results.
